To create an effective .dockerignore file for a Python project, you can exclude unnecessary files and directories to optimize your Docker image. Here's an example tailored for Python projects:
Plaintext# Ignore Python cache files
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]

# Ignore virtual environments
venv/
.env/
*.env

# Ignore logs and temporary files
*.log
*.tmp
*.swp

# Ignore compiled C extensions
*.so

# Ignore Jupyter Notebook checkpoints
.ipynb_checkpoints/

# Ignore test and coverage results
tests/
*.coverage
.coverage.*
.cache/
.nox/
.tox/

# Ignore IDE/editor-specific files
.vscode/
.idea/
*.iml

# Ignore Docker-related files (optional)
Dockerfile~
Dockerfile.distroless
.dockerignore
